The popup is rendering correctly, but the **previous/next arrow controls are no longer visible**.

The likely reason is that the old RichFaces image command generated an HTML:

```html
<input type="image">
```

Your new `p:commandLink` generates:

```html
<a>
    <img>
</a>
```

Your legacy CSS/layout—especially `styleClass="secondary"`—was probably written for an `input` or button, not for an anchor containing an image. PrimeFaces does render child components inside `p:commandLink`, so the problem is most likely the legacy CSS/layout or resource URL. ([GitHub][1])

For this particular legacy migration, the safest solution is:

> Use Jakarta Faces 4 `<h:commandButton image="...">` and attach PrimeFaces `<p:ajax>`.

Jakarta Faces 4 officially supports the `image` attribute and renders the component as `<input type="image">`, which closely matches your old RichFaces HTML structure. ([jakarta.ee][2])

# Step 1: Remove the new `p:commandLink`

Remove this entire structure:

```xhtml
<h:panelGroup id="previousNavigationPanel">

    <p:commandLink ...>

        <h:graphicImage .../>

    </p:commandLink>

</h:panelGroup>
```

We will replace it with an image command button.

---

# Step 2: Add an always-rendered wrapper

Keep one wrapper around the button:

```xhtml
<h:panelGroup id="previousNavigationPanel">
    
</h:panelGroup>
```

The wrapper is important because it can always be updated through Ajax, even when the button state changes.

---

# Step 3: Add one JSF 4 image command button

Inside the wrapper, add:

```xhtml
<h:commandButton
    id="prvImg"
    styleClass="secondary"
    disabled="#{independentContactHistoryController
                .viewEditFollowUpListBean.diablePrev}"
    action="#{independentContactHistoryController
              .navigatePreviousContactHistory}"
    image="#{independentContactHistoryController
             .viewEditFollowUpListBean.diablePrev
             ? resource['images:common/button-previous-disabled.png']
             : resource['images:common/button-previous.png']}"
    alt="Previous contact history"
    title="Previous contact history">

</h:commandButton>
```

## What this line does

```xhtml
image="#{bean.diablePrev
         ? resource['images:common/button-previous-disabled.png']
         : resource['images:common/button-previous.png']}"
```

When:

```text
diablePrev = true
```

JSF displays:

```text
button-previous-disabled.png
```

When:

```text
diablePrev = false
```

JSF displays:

```text
button-previous.png
```

You need only one button.

Jakarta Faces resolves the image URL and renders an `<input type="image">`. ([jakarta.ee][2])

---

# Step 4: Add PrimeFaces Ajax inside the button

Place this inside the `h:commandButton`:

```xhtml
<p:ajax
    process="@form"
    update=":viewEditContactHistoryForm:editFollowupNoteMainID
            :viewEditContactHistoryForm:contactViewEditSaveCloseButtonsPanelID
            :viewEditContactHistoryForm:previousNavigationPanel
            :editCloseFollowUpConfirmDialog"
    oncomplete="handlePreviousNavigationComplete(args)"/>
```

PrimeFaces `p:ajax` is an extension of the standard Faces Ajax behavior and supports PrimeFaces processing, updating, and completion callbacks. ([PrimeFaces][3])

The complete component is:

```xhtml
<h:panelGroup id="previousNavigationPanel">

    <h:commandButton
        id="prvImg"
        styleClass="secondary"

        disabled="#{independentContactHistoryController
                    .viewEditFollowUpListBean.diablePrev}"

        action="#{independentContactHistoryController
                  .navigatePreviousContactHistory}"

        image="#{independentContactHistoryController
                 .viewEditFollowUpListBean.diablePrev
                 ? resource['images:common/button-previous-disabled.png']
                 : resource['images:common/button-previous.png']}"

        alt="Previous contact history"
        title="Previous contact history">

        <p:ajax
            process="@form"

            update=":viewEditContactHistoryForm:editFollowupNoteMainID
                    :viewEditContactHistoryForm:contactViewEditSaveCloseButtonsPanelID
                    :viewEditContactHistoryForm:previousNavigationPanel
                    :editCloseFollowUpConfirmDialog"

            oncomplete="handlePreviousNavigationComplete(args)"/>

    </h:commandButton>

</h:panelGroup>
```

---

# Step 5: Preserve the existing CSS class

Keep:

```xhtml
styleClass="secondary"
```

This is important because the existing application probably contains CSS similar to:

```css
.secondary {
    /* Legacy button size, border, background or positioning */
}
```

Because `h:commandButton image="..."` renders an input element, the existing CSS is much more likely to continue working.

Do not replace it immediately with:

```xhtml
styleClass="history-navigation-link"
```

First restore the old appearance. CSS modernization can happen after the migration works.

---

# Step 6: Verify your image folder

The files must exist here:

```text
src/main/webapp/resources/images/common/
```

Complete structure:

```text
src
└── main
    └── webapp
        └── resources
            └── images
                └── common
                    ├── button-previous.png
                    └── button-previous-disabled.png
```

The resource expression:

```xhtml
#{resource['images:common/button-previous.png']}
```

means:

```text
Library name: images

Resource name:
common/button-previous.png
```

Jakarta Faces supports resource-library references for image resources. ([jakarta.ee][4])

---

# Step 7: Add the Java wrapper method

In `IndependentContactHistoryController`, add:

```java
import org.primefaces.PrimeFaces;

public void navigatePreviousContactHistory() {

    /*
     * Call the existing business logic.
     */
    getContactHistoryForNoteIDPreNext("prev");

    /*
     * Send the latest dataModified value to JavaScript.
     */
    PrimeFaces.current()
            .ajax()
            .addCallbackParam(
                    "dataModified",
                    dataModified
            );
}
```

When `dataModified` is accessible only through a getter:

```java
public void navigatePreviousContactHistory() {

    getContactHistoryForNoteIDPreNext("prev");

    PrimeFaces.current()
            .ajax()
            .addCallbackParam(
                    "dataModified",
                    getDataModified()
            );
}
```

Use only the version that matches your controller.

PrimeFaces callback parameters are made available through the JavaScript Ajax callback arguments. ([PrimeFaces][5])

---

# Step 8: Add the JavaScript completion function

Add this once to the XHTML:

```xhtml
<h:outputScript target="body">

    function handlePreviousNavigationComplete(args) {

        setDatepicker();

        if (args &amp;&amp; args.dataModified === true) {

            showConfirmationContactHistoryPopup(
                'viewEditPrevFollowUpConfirmDialog',
                400
            );
        }
    }

</h:outputScript>
```

Use:

```xhtml
&amp;&amp;
```

because this is an XHTML/XML document.

Do not use your old expression:

```xhtml
#{independentContactHistoryController.dataModified == 'false'}
```

That compares the property with a String and can also use a value rendered before the current Ajax operation completes.

---

# Step 9: Remove manual button disabling

Remove:

```xhtml
onclick="this.disabled=true;"
```

For the first test, do not manually disable the image input.

The PrimeFaces Ajax queue processes requests sequentially by default, so first confirm that the button displays and functions correctly. ([PrimeFaces][6])

After everything works, duplicate-click handling can be added separately without interfering with the image submission.

